<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10142e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10142e">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10142e"> 142(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> digs towards him / white = dirty</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Now watch the same man beginning to cultivate. There he is gripping his spade, and digging away in the opposite manner to ours&mdash;that is to say, <mark>he digs towards</mark> and not away from himself. Of course, after sending the earth flying at this rate, he is now dirty, but that means that he is white; for a negro is black when he is clean and <mark>white when he is dirty</mark>. <small> Daniel Crawford, <a name="DCTB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#DCTB"><cite title="source">Thinking Black</cite></a> (1912) 71</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01070h" href="c01all.htm#c01070h">VI.C.01:070(h)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
